        ". Even a partially ionized gas in which as little as 42% of the particles are ionized can have the characteristics of a plasma . The plasmas used in spectrochemical analysis are essentially electrically neutral, with each positive charge on an ion balanced by a free electron. In these plasmas the positive ions are almost all singly charged and there are few negative ions, so there are nearly equal amounts of ions and electrons in each unit volume of plasma.     What makes Inductively Coupled Plasma Mass Spectrometry unique to other forms of inorganic mass spectrometry is its ability to sample the analyte continuously, without interruption. This is in contrast to other forms of inorganic mass spectrometry; ": null
